WEBVTT

00:01.752 --> 00:03.879
[♪♪♪]

00:03.879 --> 00:05.255
I heard
our apartment

00:05.255 --> 00:07.007
is going to be
a lot of work.

00:07.007 --> 00:09.343
Kurt will pay you back just
as soon as we're settled.

00:09.343 --> 00:11.971
Mrs. Lawson, all you have to do
is be a good neighbor.

00:11.971 --> 00:15.140
Just the same, we don't
like taking charity.

00:15.140 --> 00:17.100
We can talk about
all that later.

00:17.100 --> 00:18.727
[VOICES RISING]

00:18.727 --> 00:20.521
What is this new piece
you've acquired?

00:20.521 --> 00:21.730
Isn't it beguiling?

00:21.730 --> 00:23.148
That's...
one word for it.

00:23.148 --> 00:25.233
Excuse me.

00:26.986 --> 00:28.320
It's amazing

00:28.320 --> 00:30.322
you would buy that
for yourself.

00:30.322 --> 00:32.908
Well, I needed something special
to wear for Christmas Eve.

00:32.908 --> 00:34.576
Sorry to interrupt, ladies,

00:34.576 --> 00:36.787
but I need to speak
to Mrs. Blakeley for a second.

00:36.787 --> 00:38.998
Of course.
Thank you.

00:38.998 --> 00:41.542
That is an interesting
piece of jewelry.

00:41.542 --> 00:43.669
Thank you, Constable.
Is it new?

00:43.669 --> 00:46.296
I bought it from that lovely
peddler, Mr. Bailey.

00:46.296 --> 00:48.298
He said it's one
of a kind.

00:48.298 --> 00:49.675
I bet it is.

00:49.675 --> 00:51.343
Too bad there's
only one, though.

00:51.343 --> 00:53.804
It would look great with
the gown Elizabeth is wearing

00:53.804 --> 00:55.389
to the Mountie Ball.

00:55.389 --> 00:58.308
Oh... Oh,
I'm sorry, I--

00:58.308 --> 00:59.768
I know
that you can't

00:59.768 --> 01:01.854
put a price on something
like that, Mrs. Blakeley,

01:01.854 --> 01:04.231
but I'd be willing to give you
twice what you paid for it.

01:04.231 --> 01:06.901
It would mean
a lot to me.

01:06.901 --> 01:09.277
And then you could get yourself
something even nicer.

01:09.277 --> 01:10.905
Well...

01:10.905 --> 01:14.533
there was a dragonfly pendant,
a truly stunning piece.

01:14.533 --> 01:16.035
But it cost...

01:16.035 --> 01:18.495
$10.

01:19.454 --> 01:21.749
You know what,
Mrs. Blakeley?

01:21.749 --> 01:24.710
I think you deserve to have
a stunning Christmas.

01:25.836 --> 01:28.463
Well, if you insist.

01:29.840 --> 01:31.341
[DASHER BARKS]

01:35.679 --> 01:37.848
Does Dasher know any tricks?

01:37.848 --> 01:39.641
Most dogs like to play catch.

01:39.641 --> 01:41.518
Not with this ball.

01:41.518 --> 01:42.770
Hey, Cody.

01:42.770 --> 01:44.312
Aren't you late
for school?

01:44.312 --> 01:45.940
I guess so.

01:45.940 --> 01:48.233
What can I do
for you, Constable?

01:48.233 --> 01:50.151
Well, I just spoke
to Mrs. Blakeley,

01:50.151 --> 01:51.612
and she told me

01:51.612 --> 01:55.240
that you sold her
this special piece of jewelry.

01:55.240 --> 01:57.200
So I did.
Hard to forget that one.

01:57.200 --> 01:58.827
You mind telling me
where you got it?

01:58.827 --> 02:01.371
Oh, I buy and sell
a lot of things.

02:01.371 --> 02:02.706
Hard to keep track
of them all.

02:02.706 --> 02:04.959
Really?

02:04.959 --> 02:07.711
Because this happens
to be stolen property.

02:08.712 --> 02:11.131
I'm sorry to hear that.

02:11.131 --> 02:13.050
Maybe the circuit judge
can jog your memory,

02:13.050 --> 02:15.052
but I'm afraid he won't be
coming though town

02:15.052 --> 02:16.553
till after Christmas.

02:16.553 --> 02:18.555
I still can't remember.

02:18.555 --> 02:20.015
That's a shame,

02:20.015 --> 02:22.183
'cause you know
I'm going to have to arrest you.

02:22.183 --> 02:24.519
Well, you gotta do
what you gotta do.

02:27.439 --> 02:28.899
[♪♪♪]

02:47.292 --> 02:49.336
May I have your attention,
please?

02:49.336 --> 02:51.964
All right, everyone.

02:51.964 --> 02:55.968
It is time to assign the parts
for the nativity pageant.

02:55.968 --> 02:58.971
Now, several of you have shown
excellent Christmas spirit,

02:58.971 --> 03:01.098
and I am
very, very proud of you.

03:01.098 --> 03:03.266
All right. Ruby...

03:03.266 --> 03:05.477
you'll be playing
the role of Mary.

03:05.477 --> 03:07.604
Hattie and Anna...

03:07.604 --> 03:09.397
there will be two angels
this year

03:09.397 --> 03:12.526
because the two of you
have both been angels.

03:12.526 --> 03:14.361
Cody, you'll be playing
one of the Wise Men,

03:14.361 --> 03:16.530
and Robert and Timmy,
you will also be Wise Men.

03:16.530 --> 03:19.033
Do we get
to ride camels?

03:19.033 --> 03:22.327
Ha. I'm afraid they were
fresh out of camels in Buxton.

03:22.327 --> 03:24.038
But your new costumes

03:24.038 --> 03:27.374
should be arriving
first thing tomorrow morning.

03:28.375 --> 03:29.710
[DOOR OPENS]

03:31.962 --> 03:35.007
Um, Emily, would you mind
finishing reading the cast list?

03:35.007 --> 03:36.424
Thank you.

03:36.424 --> 03:38.468
Opal, you're going to be
the little drummer girl.

03:38.468 --> 03:40.428
If this is about
the gown for the Mountie Ball,

03:40.428 --> 03:42.430
I'm kind of in the middle
of something.

03:42.430 --> 03:43.891
Not at all.

03:43.891 --> 03:46.060
Dottie's finishing
the alterations as we speak.

03:46.060 --> 03:48.062
No, I am here
because Lee told me

03:48.062 --> 03:49.354
you were in desperate need

03:49.354 --> 03:51.356
of help with
the Christmas festivities.

03:51.356 --> 03:53.233
Well, it wasn't really
an emergency.

03:53.233 --> 03:54.943
Now, I know it's hard
for you to admit

03:54.943 --> 03:56.945
that you are in over your head,
and you don't want

03:56.945 --> 03:58.989
to exhaust yourself
before the Mountie Ball.

03:58.989 --> 04:00.490
You certainly don't want

04:00.490 --> 04:02.784
any more of those unsightly
little worry lines...

04:02.784 --> 04:04.411
I don't have worry lines.

04:04.411 --> 04:06.413
Of course you don't.

04:06.413 --> 04:07.873
Thankfully,

04:07.873 --> 04:10.042
I have done dozens
of these Christmas pageants,

04:10.042 --> 04:11.877
and I am ready to jump right in.

04:11.877 --> 04:14.755
Actually, what I really need

04:14.755 --> 04:17.758
is some help stringing popcorn
for the Christmas tree.

04:17.758 --> 04:19.551
Stringing popcorn?

04:19.551 --> 04:22.387
Mm-hmm. Jump right in.

04:36.193 --> 04:37.736
Henry.

04:37.736 --> 04:40.488
I told you I didn't want
to talk about any town business.

04:40.488 --> 04:41.990
That's not why I'm here.

04:42.991 --> 04:44.826
Why did you
fire Dottie?

04:44.826 --> 04:46.245
Fired Dottie

04:46.245 --> 04:48.247
because I no longer had use
for her services.

04:48.247 --> 04:49.790
But she was trying
to take care of you

04:49.790 --> 04:51.291
until you got back
on your feet.

04:51.291 --> 04:52.500
And why are you here?

04:52.500 --> 04:54.419
You here because
you care about me?

04:56.671 --> 04:58.840
Is that so hard to believe?

04:58.840 --> 05:00.092
A while ago,

05:00.092 --> 05:02.177
that might have meant
something to me.

05:02.177 --> 05:03.470
A while ago?

05:03.470 --> 05:04.679
Believe it or not,

05:04.679 --> 05:06.223
I cared about
what happened to you

05:06.223 --> 05:07.849
after your husband passed.

05:07.849 --> 05:10.310
That's one of the reasons
why I invested in your cafe.

05:10.310 --> 05:11.561
It was a business deal.

05:11.561 --> 05:13.814
You were just trying
to make money.

05:13.814 --> 05:15.607
Well, you can believe
whatever you like.

05:15.607 --> 05:18.693
Henry, I know that you're upset
about a lot of things.

05:18.693 --> 05:20.279
Here's
what you know.

05:20.279 --> 05:22.447
What you know
is that I don't want your help.

05:22.447 --> 05:24.866
You're here because
you want to feel good

05:24.866 --> 05:26.660
about the fact
that you made an effort.

05:26.660 --> 05:28.369
You're here

05:28.369 --> 05:30.455
because you want to be able
to go to sleep at night,

05:30.455 --> 05:33.625
comforted by the fact
that you know that you tried.

05:33.625 --> 05:36.128
You're just saying that because
you think I took your job.

05:36.128 --> 05:38.839
Then why can't we just
stop playing games here?

05:40.548 --> 05:42.341
Why can't you just admit
that you enjoy

05:42.341 --> 05:44.886
feeling morally superior
to the rest of us?

05:44.886 --> 05:46.847
You're here for you.

05:46.847 --> 05:48.223
Not for me.

05:48.223 --> 05:50.267
For you.

05:50.267 --> 05:51.852
If you really believe that,

05:51.852 --> 05:53.937
then there is
nothing more to say.

05:53.937 --> 05:56.231
Well, I really believe that,
so I guess we're done.

05:56.231 --> 05:57.732
We're done.

05:58.817 --> 06:00.986
[HUFFS]

06:02.779 --> 06:04.614
[DOOR OPENS, THEN SHUTS]

06:06.407 --> 06:08.035
Oh!

06:09.368 --> 06:12.622
[♪♪♪]

06:20.922 --> 06:22.883
SAM:
Sure could use
some more coffee.

06:24.759 --> 06:26.303
Really?

06:29.014 --> 06:31.058
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY]

06:39.398 --> 06:42.027
Most people
don't like my coffee.

06:42.027 --> 06:44.905
Well, most people
forget to be grateful.

06:45.947 --> 06:47.657
That's true enough.

06:49.868 --> 06:52.204
Got any family, Sam?

06:52.204 --> 06:53.955
The world
is my family.

06:53.955 --> 06:56.208
The world's your family.

06:56.208 --> 06:58.501
You sure are
hard to read.

06:58.501 --> 07:00.003
What I do is who I am.

07:00.003 --> 07:01.255
[CHUCKLES]

07:01.255 --> 07:03.173
Got a special
occasion coming up?

07:05.133 --> 07:07.052
The Mountie
Christmas Ball.

07:07.052 --> 07:09.179
I bet you're taking
that pretty schoolteacher.

07:09.179 --> 07:10.471
Yep.

07:10.471 --> 07:12.224
Gonna hire a carriage,
go in style.

07:12.224 --> 07:13.474
I got it
all planned out.

07:13.474 --> 07:14.976
Yeah, you seem like
the kind of guy

07:14.976 --> 07:16.603
who always has
everything planned.

07:16.603 --> 07:17.896
I guess I do.

07:17.896 --> 07:19.398
Plans are a funny thing,
you know.

07:19.398 --> 07:20.941
How's that?

07:20.941 --> 07:23.235
Well, they don't always
turn out the way you expect.

07:23.235 --> 07:24.652
Take me, for instance.

07:24.652 --> 07:26.780
I didn't plan on
spending the night in jail.

07:26.780 --> 07:28.615
No, I suppose you didn't.

07:28.615 --> 07:31.492
A few hours ago, I was hungry,
cold.

07:31.492 --> 07:32.911
Now I got
a roof over my head,

07:32.911 --> 07:34.121
a hot meal.

07:34.121 --> 07:36.664
Sometimes,
what you don't want

07:36.664 --> 07:40.127
turns out to be exactly
the thing you need.

07:40.127 --> 07:42.045
It's kinda the story of my life.

07:42.045 --> 07:43.297
How's that?

07:43.297 --> 07:44.756
Well, time was,

07:44.756 --> 07:45.924
like most people,

07:45.924 --> 07:48.509
I wanted to be rich
and powerful.

07:48.509 --> 07:49.928
Important.

07:49.928 --> 07:52.347
Well, I never got
to be those things,

07:52.347 --> 07:55.809
so I had to make
a different life for myself.

07:55.809 --> 07:58.353
Had to figure out
what I really wanted.

07:58.353 --> 08:00.397
Well...

08:00.397 --> 08:03.400
I guess we all got to figure
that out sooner or later.

08:03.400 --> 08:05.068
Yep.

08:05.068 --> 08:07.695
And when life doesn't go
the way you want,

08:07.695 --> 08:10.907
it's a good time to stop
and think about it.

08:13.327 --> 08:15.912
[♪♪♪]

08:23.128 --> 08:25.797
♪ Five golden rings ♪

08:25.797 --> 08:27.632
♪ Four calling birds ♪

08:27.632 --> 08:28.925
♪ Three French hens ♪

08:28.925 --> 08:30.510
♪ Two turtle doves ♪

08:30.510 --> 08:34.097
ALL THREE:
♪ And a partridge
In a pear tree ♪

08:34.097 --> 08:36.016
You're a really good
singer, Mr. Avery.

08:36.016 --> 08:37.517
And a good babysitter.

08:37.517 --> 08:38.768
Well, thanks to you both.

08:38.768 --> 08:40.395
Now off to bed
with you, young man.

08:40.395 --> 08:41.729
It's late.
Good night.

08:41.729 --> 08:43.106
'Night!

08:43.106 --> 08:44.441
[EXHALES HEAVILY]

08:44.441 --> 08:45.650
As a rule,

08:45.650 --> 08:47.486
it's good to have dinner
before midnight.

08:47.486 --> 08:48.736
Well, with the town budget,

08:48.736 --> 08:50.197
committee meetings,
hearings,

08:50.197 --> 08:51.531
and all these invoices to pay,

08:51.531 --> 08:53.616
I must've lost track of time.

08:53.616 --> 08:56.077
So, how was your visit
with Henry today?

08:56.077 --> 08:58.913
Or should I ask?

08:58.913 --> 09:01.500
Well, let's just say
it wasn't pleasant.

09:01.500 --> 09:04.627
Abigail, forget about Gowen.

09:04.627 --> 09:06.004
You're trying too hard.

09:07.422 --> 09:09.090
You're absolutely right.

09:09.090 --> 09:10.884
And there's so much to do.

09:10.884 --> 09:13.678
I had no idea how much work
went into running a town.

09:13.678 --> 09:15.805
Well, that's
my point exactly.

09:15.805 --> 09:18.808
Gowen should be thanking you
for relieving him of his duties.

09:18.808 --> 09:21.478
And I should be thanking you
for babysitting Cody.

09:21.478 --> 09:22.770
And for this soup!

09:22.770 --> 09:24.189
It's almost as good as mine!

09:24.189 --> 09:26.774
I won't tell if you won't.

09:26.774 --> 09:28.776
[CHUCKLES]

09:28.776 --> 09:30.653
Mm!

09:33.114 --> 09:36.076
[♪♪♪]

09:40.163 --> 09:41.664
Jack!

09:41.664 --> 09:44.000
Rosemary. You're up early.

09:44.000 --> 09:47.045
I didn't catch a wink of sleep
after I heard what had happened.

09:47.045 --> 09:49.297
How could you arrest
that lovely old man?

09:49.297 --> 09:51.091
Mr. Bailey?

09:51.091 --> 09:53.468
Just doing my job.

09:53.468 --> 09:56.054
You have made
a terrible mistake.

09:56.054 --> 09:57.764
How so?

09:57.764 --> 09:59.433
He didn't steal that...

09:59.433 --> 10:01.560
oh, horrible pin.

10:02.769 --> 10:05.146
How do you know
what he stole, Rosemary?

10:05.146 --> 10:07.690
[CHUCKLES]

10:07.690 --> 10:09.443
Funny thing, that.

10:09.443 --> 10:11.736
Amuse me.

10:11.736 --> 10:13.363
Well...

10:13.363 --> 10:16.824
I just happened to be
straightening out Lee's things,

10:16.824 --> 10:18.243
when, lo and behold,

10:18.243 --> 10:20.120
I accidentally

10:20.120 --> 10:22.539
found this small box.

10:22.539 --> 10:25.708
You accidentally
]unwrapped it and opened it?

10:25.708 --> 10:29.170
The details aren't important.
What is important is...

10:29.170 --> 10:31.214
have you seen...

10:31.214 --> 10:33.800
that-- that thing?

10:34.468 --> 10:35.760
I have.

10:35.760 --> 10:37.387
[SIGHS HEAVILY]
Well, then you know

10:37.387 --> 10:39.055
I could never have worn it.

10:39.055 --> 10:41.266
So you sold it to Sam?

10:41.266 --> 10:43.101
Well, I didn't want
to hurt Lee's feelings.

10:43.101 --> 10:45.979
I thought that, if he thought
that he had lost it,

10:45.979 --> 10:48.064
well, then he would just
pick something else out.

10:48.064 --> 10:49.941
something a little less,
ugh, terrifying.

10:49.941 --> 10:52.277
I know he means well!

10:52.277 --> 10:53.653
Oh, Jack!

10:53.653 --> 10:55.363
I didn't know what to do!

10:55.363 --> 10:57.824
I'm gonna tell you exactly
what you're gonna do.

10:57.824 --> 11:00.785
Your husband bought you
a very special gift

11:00.785 --> 11:02.370
for your first
Christmas together.

11:02.370 --> 11:03.955
So...

11:03.955 --> 11:06.207
you are going to put it
right back where you found it,

11:06.207 --> 11:08.376
then, on Christmas morning,
when he gives it to you,

11:08.376 --> 11:10.420
you will act surprised
and delighted.

11:10.420 --> 11:12.755
"Surprised and delighted"?

11:13.756 --> 11:16.217
You're a very talented actress.

11:17.676 --> 11:20.263
It'll be the performance
of a lifetime.

11:21.181 --> 11:22.557
Do you promise

11:22.557 --> 11:24.725
not to say a word
about what happened?

11:24.725 --> 11:27.103
My lips are sealed.

11:27.895 --> 11:30.023
[♪♪♪]

11:31.566 --> 11:32.942
You should've told me

11:32.942 --> 11:34.486
Rosemary Coulter
sold you the pin.

11:34.486 --> 11:35.903
Oh, it wouldn't
have been right!

11:35.903 --> 11:37.238
Because?

11:37.238 --> 11:38.490
Well, the way I see it,

11:38.490 --> 11:40.116
it gave the young lady
an opportunity

11:40.116 --> 11:42.494
to learn a lesson
about telling the truth,

11:42.494 --> 11:45.246
which is exactly what
she needed for Christmas.

11:45.246 --> 11:49.083
So it all worked out
the way it was supposed to.

11:49.083 --> 11:51.878
Come on, Dasher.

11:52.920 --> 11:55.048
[DOOR CLOSES]

12:03.097 --> 12:05.266
Pastor!

12:05.266 --> 12:06.725
You're just the man
I want to see.

12:06.725 --> 12:08.186
I got something for you.

12:08.186 --> 12:09.937
I don't think you have
anything I need.

12:09.937 --> 12:12.232
Don't be too sure.
What do you say?

12:12.232 --> 12:13.774
A man of God can
always use a Bible.

12:13.774 --> 12:15.235
And I'll let it go
for cheap.

12:15.235 --> 12:17.362
That's okay. I've got
plenty of those at church.

12:17.362 --> 12:18.737
Well,
it is pretty old.

12:18.737 --> 12:20.448
I got it from
Granville Penitentiary.

12:20.448 --> 12:23.742
They were giving away
some old books.

12:23.742 --> 12:25.370
Wait.

12:25.370 --> 12:27.830
Do you mind
if I look at that for a second?

12:30.709 --> 12:33.503
[♪♪♪]

12:34.671 --> 12:37.131
I did time at Granville.

12:37.131 --> 12:39.718
Lot of people did
time at Granville.

12:39.718 --> 12:43.054
I saved it because of
the inscription on the back.

12:46.224 --> 12:48.560
The Saint Francis prayer.

12:48.560 --> 12:51.062
"Lord, let me be
an instrument of Thy peace.

12:51.062 --> 12:52.855
"Where there is hatred,
let me sow love,

12:52.855 --> 12:54.399
"where there is doubt, faith,

12:54.399 --> 12:57.402
where there is despair, hope."

12:57.402 --> 12:58.819
It's a favorite of mine.

12:58.819 --> 13:00.280
Mine, too.

13:00.280 --> 13:02.616
Which is why I wrote it there.

13:03.575 --> 13:05.493
[ASTONISHED CHUCKLE]

13:05.493 --> 13:07.036
This was my bible.

13:07.036 --> 13:08.955
Is that right?

13:08.955 --> 13:10.749
Oh...

13:10.749 --> 13:13.752
You must've changed
a lot of lives with this book.

13:13.752 --> 13:17.046
And I have a feeling
you're gonna change a lot more.

13:17.046 --> 13:18.923
Like that friend
you were telling me about,

13:18.923 --> 13:20.508
the one with the little boy.

13:20.508 --> 13:22.843
She left without telling anyone
where she was going,

13:22.843 --> 13:24.387
there's no way to find her.

13:24.387 --> 13:27.724
Three wise men found Bethlehem
by following a star.

13:27.724 --> 13:28.975
Well, they had a lot of help.

13:28.975 --> 13:30.393
So have you, my friend.

13:30.393 --> 13:32.228
How much
you want for that?

13:32.228 --> 13:33.480
Oh, take it.

13:33.480 --> 13:34.855
The way I look at it,

13:34.855 --> 13:36.899
I'm just returning it
to its rightful owner.

13:36.899 --> 13:39.277
Good morning,
Miss Yost.

13:40.320 --> 13:41.655
Katie!

13:43.615 --> 13:47.285
Katie, when-when Nancy Tucker
came to you for supplies,

13:47.285 --> 13:49.329
did she happen to mention
where she was headed?

13:49.329 --> 13:50.829
I don't think so.

13:51.998 --> 13:53.500
Wait! She did say

13:53.500 --> 13:56.336
she needed enough rations
to get to Albert Falls.

13:56.336 --> 13:58.129
Albert Falls.

13:58.129 --> 13:59.506
Thanks.

14:02.258 --> 14:05.886
Looks like the pastor
just found his star after all.

14:05.886 --> 14:08.723
[♪♪♪]

14:12.686 --> 14:14.979
Oh, it's pretty snug.
You want to hand me that mallet?

14:14.979 --> 14:16.897
Yeah.

14:16.897 --> 14:19.192
Thank you.
Yeah.

14:20.610 --> 14:23.279
[♪♪♪]

14:25.948 --> 14:28.034
[MALLET AND HAMMER POUNDING]

14:30.370 --> 14:33.080
[WOOD GROANING]

14:33.080 --> 14:34.457
Watch out!

14:34.457 --> 14:35.750
[CREAKING]

14:35.750 --> 14:37.502
[CRASHING]

14:38.294 --> 14:40.963
[♪♪♪]

14:47.011 --> 14:48.888
The freight
wagon's late.

14:48.888 --> 14:51.683
That silly wagon
is always running late.

14:51.683 --> 14:54.561
I'm sure it'll
be here in no time.

14:56.062 --> 14:58.064
I want to make sure everything's
taken care of

14:58.064 --> 14:59.566
before we leave
for the ball tonight.

14:59.566 --> 15:00.983
Don't you worry
about it.

15:00.983 --> 15:02.736
I will tie up
any loose ends.

15:02.736 --> 15:04.278
You will?

15:04.278 --> 15:05.655
Of course.
You asked for my help,

15:05.655 --> 15:07.741
and Christmas is
the season for giving.

15:09.701 --> 15:11.327
Pardon me.
I thought I should

15:11.327 --> 15:12.579
deliver this in person.

15:12.579 --> 15:13.830
Thank you.

15:13.830 --> 15:15.749
"Train derailed
outside Union City.

15:15.749 --> 15:17.333
Track closed."

15:17.333 --> 15:19.794
There won't be any deliveries
till after Christmas.

15:19.794 --> 15:22.046
Oh!

15:27.009 --> 15:29.220
[♪♪♪]

15:29.220 --> 15:32.014
Everyone's going
to be so disappointed.

15:32.014 --> 15:33.433
It's not that bad.

15:33.433 --> 15:35.309
Yes, it is.

15:35.309 --> 15:36.936
What am I going
to tell the children?

15:36.936 --> 15:39.188
Timmy wanted
a train set,

15:39.188 --> 15:40.940
and Ruby had
her heart set

15:40.940 --> 15:42.483
on a doll's house.

15:42.483 --> 15:43.651
And poor Maggie,

15:43.651 --> 15:46.279
all she wanted
was a "Biddy Betsy."

15:46.279 --> 15:49.407
Maggie isn't
going to get her doll?

15:49.407 --> 15:52.076
Cody, why don't you run outside
and play for a little while?

15:55.204 --> 15:56.790
The stove I ordered
for the Lawsons

15:56.790 --> 15:58.332
was on that train.

15:58.332 --> 16:00.376
They'll understand.

16:00.376 --> 16:01.711
I know, but it's...

16:01.711 --> 16:03.797
it's so unfair.

16:05.757 --> 16:08.008
I better let Jack know.

16:14.432 --> 16:15.892
No, we're fine,

16:15.892 --> 16:18.269
but we could use some help
shoring up the beam.

16:18.269 --> 16:20.104
[SIGHING]

16:20.104 --> 16:21.397
Excuse me.

16:21.397 --> 16:22.732
Elizabeth!

16:22.732 --> 16:24.108
Jack--

16:24.108 --> 16:25.443
I've got some bad news.

16:25.443 --> 16:26.611
You heard
about the train?

16:26.611 --> 16:28.195
It gets worse.
The beam fell

16:28.195 --> 16:29.489
at the apartment

16:29.489 --> 16:31.198
we were fixing up
for the Lawson family.

16:31.198 --> 16:33.367
Now, we're all okay, but we're
behind schedule.

16:33.367 --> 16:36.036
What are we gonna do?
Whatever we have to.

16:36.036 --> 16:37.580
Now, we said
we're gonna make this

16:37.580 --> 16:39.916
a special Christmas
for the town,

16:39.916 --> 16:42.585
we're gonna deliver.

16:42.585 --> 16:43.920
Even if
we have to work

16:43.920 --> 16:45.713
straight through
till Christmas Eve.

16:45.713 --> 16:47.841
But the Mountie Ball...

16:47.841 --> 16:49.884
Yeah.

16:49.884 --> 16:52.595
I really
want us to go...

16:52.595 --> 16:56.056
but I think this
is more important.

16:56.056 --> 16:59.226
I'm so glad you said that.
We can't leave now.

16:59.226 --> 17:01.354
So, what's the next step?

17:02.104 --> 17:04.858
[♪♪♪]

17:07.777 --> 17:09.320
[BUSTLING CHATTER]

17:09.320 --> 17:10.989
If I could have
everyone's attention...

17:10.989 --> 17:13.240
Just because the freight wagon
didn't come through

17:13.240 --> 17:15.159
doesn't mean
we have to give up on Christmas.

17:15.159 --> 17:16.995
It just means
we have to change our plans,

17:16.995 --> 17:18.245
because everything we need,

17:18.245 --> 17:20.206
we have right here,
in Hope Valley.

17:20.206 --> 17:22.249
Where are we going to get
toys for the children?

17:22.249 --> 17:23.751
Well, we'll
make them ourselves.

17:23.751 --> 17:24.961
There simply isn't time!

17:24.961 --> 17:26.504
Christmas Eve
is tomorrow night!

17:26.504 --> 17:28.130
[MURMURING IN AGREEMENT]

17:28.130 --> 17:29.841
We can do it
if we all pitch in.

17:29.841 --> 17:31.175
When I was a girl,
we made dolls

17:31.175 --> 17:33.052
from cornhusks
and clothespins.

17:33.052 --> 17:35.013
Well, there's plenty
of scrap wood at the mill

17:35.013 --> 17:37.097
to build toys with,
if we want.

17:37.097 --> 17:39.099
Well, what about the new homes
for the settlers?

17:39.099 --> 17:41.101
I heard they can't
be finished in time.

17:41.101 --> 17:42.478
Anything can be fixed.

17:42.478 --> 17:44.188
All we need are
a few extra sets of hands.

17:44.188 --> 17:45.815
What are we going
to do about the stove

17:45.815 --> 17:47.441
for Kurt
and Wilma's place?

17:47.441 --> 17:49.360
I've kept my old stove,

17:49.360 --> 17:51.111
but the bottom's
rusted out.

17:51.111 --> 17:53.197
JACK:
We've got a new welder in town.

17:53.197 --> 17:55.033
Mr. Edwards,
I'll see what he can do.

17:55.033 --> 17:57.911
What about costumes
for the nativity pageant?

17:57.911 --> 17:59.579
I could probably
whip something up.

17:59.579 --> 18:01.539
I have a wonderful idea!

18:01.539 --> 18:04.500
Why don't we hold
the Nativity Pageant right here?

18:04.500 --> 18:06.711
We could decorate it
to look like an old barn.

18:06.711 --> 18:08.295
It'll be
like a real manger.

18:08.295 --> 18:09.923
There's still
Christmas Eve dinner.

18:09.923 --> 18:11.173
For about
a hundred of us.

18:11.173 --> 18:12.717
BILL:
Leave that to me.

18:12.717 --> 18:14.802
Everyone go home
and look through your pantries.

18:14.802 --> 18:17.430
Go to your neighbor's house,
and look through their pantries.

18:17.430 --> 18:19.306
Whatever you can spare,
bring to the cafe.

18:19.306 --> 18:21.059
I think this calls for a vote.

18:21.059 --> 18:23.394
All those in favor of
saving Christmas, say "aye."

18:23.394 --> 18:24.979
ALL:
Aye!

18:24.979 --> 18:28.107
[CHATTER RISES]

18:40.453 --> 18:42.288
What can I do for
you, young man?

18:42.288 --> 18:44.290
I need a toy.
Do you have any left?

18:44.290 --> 18:45.875
I'm sorry,
it's almost Christmas.

18:45.875 --> 18:47.167
I'm all out of toys.

18:47.167 --> 18:50.254
Oh.

18:50.254 --> 18:52.715
Uh, what was it
you were looking for?

18:53.758 --> 18:56.761
A doll.
It was for a friend.

18:56.761 --> 18:58.638
I see! You're trying
to be a good boy

18:58.638 --> 19:00.514
so you get a part
in that Christmas pageant.

19:00.514 --> 19:02.475
I already
got the part.

19:02.475 --> 19:04.852
Then you don't need
to give her the doll.

19:04.852 --> 19:06.771
I just want to, I guess.

19:06.771 --> 19:09.774
And I promised she could have
a tea party at Miss Abigail's.

19:11.818 --> 19:13.444
Now that I think on it...

19:13.444 --> 19:15.154
I just might have
something left.

19:15.154 --> 19:16.823
Let me check.

19:16.823 --> 19:19.867
Oh. It's not very fancy,
I'm afraid.

19:19.867 --> 19:23.121
Just an old "Biddy Betsy" doll.

19:23.121 --> 19:24.455
That's just what she wanted!

19:24.455 --> 19:25.832
Imagine that.

19:25.832 --> 19:27.125
Can I buy it?

19:27.125 --> 19:29.251
Uh, it's my last one.

19:30.628 --> 19:32.088
[♪♪♪]

19:34.132 --> 19:35.633
I've got seven cents!

19:37.176 --> 19:40.013
She's worth more than that,
wouldn't you say?

19:40.013 --> 19:41.848
It's all I've got.

19:42.974 --> 19:46.268
Maybe we could make a trade.

19:46.268 --> 19:47.728
[♪♪♪]

19:54.694 --> 19:58.072
[QUIET CONVERSATIONS,
INDISTINCT]

20:01.367 --> 20:03.452
I brought these cotton balls
from the infirmary.

20:03.452 --> 20:05.788
I thought we could use them
as stuffing for the dolls.

20:05.788 --> 20:07.165
Oh! They will do very nicely.

20:07.165 --> 20:08.582
I haven't done
much sewing,

20:08.582 --> 20:10.376
apart from stitching up
cuts and scrapes.

20:10.376 --> 20:12.419
We're very glad you're here.
Indeed.

20:12.419 --> 20:15.464
I've never built a house
for a doll before.

20:15.464 --> 20:17.257
Oh, It's just like
building a real house.

20:17.257 --> 20:19.259
Only, um, smaller.

20:19.259 --> 20:21.971
Yes, but a real house
has a set of plans.

20:21.971 --> 20:24.515
I took the liberty
of drawing something up.

20:24.515 --> 20:26.059
It's got the flavor

20:26.059 --> 20:28.394
of a Frank Lloyd Wright
Colonial Revival.

20:28.394 --> 20:30.813
[♪♪♪]

20:30.813 --> 20:32.982
Great. Great.

20:34.441 --> 20:36.318
Ah, this is
pretty much a goner.

20:36.318 --> 20:38.487
Bottom's all rusted out.

20:38.487 --> 20:42.241
Yeah, and the firebox
is cracked, too.

20:42.241 --> 20:44.118
So?

20:44.118 --> 20:46.286
How long do you think
it'll take to fix?

20:46.286 --> 20:48.039
Well, maybe a couple of days.

20:48.039 --> 20:49.874
Can you get it done
by tomorrow night?

20:50.833 --> 20:52.292
I'll do my best.

20:52.292 --> 20:53.753
Thanks, George.

20:54.712 --> 20:57.006
[HOOVES CLOPPING]

20:57.006 --> 20:58.632
Frank, you look like
you're headed

20:58.632 --> 20:59.967
somewhere
in a hurry.

20:59.967 --> 21:02.011
Nancy Tucker.
Giddyap!

21:02.011 --> 21:04.430
[QUIETLY]
Good luck.

21:04.430 --> 21:07.474
So what have we got?
Canned fish, canned oysters,

21:07.474 --> 21:10.394
more canned fish, more oysters,
lots and lots of beans,

21:10.394 --> 21:12.730
and then there's some bacon
from the Campbells' farm.

21:12.730 --> 21:14.732
Not much of it.

21:14.732 --> 21:17.359
Ned Yost brought over the flour
and the sugar and the potatoes,

21:17.359 --> 21:18.652
but he says
it's the last of it.

21:18.652 --> 21:20.238
And you knocked
on every door?

21:20.238 --> 21:22.489
Everyone was counting on
the freight wagon, so there

21:22.489 --> 21:24.992
wasn't much left. How do
we make a Christmas Eve banquet

21:24.992 --> 21:27.327
out of this?

21:28.370 --> 21:30.206
We start with
an oyster soup,

21:30.206 --> 21:32.166
fish stew, potato pie,

21:32.166 --> 21:33.375
bacon and beans,

21:33.375 --> 21:34.627
and finish it with

21:34.627 --> 21:36.670
a carrot-and-chicken
surprise casserole.

21:36.670 --> 21:38.505
But we don't have
any chicken.

21:38.505 --> 21:40.674
That's the surprise.

21:40.674 --> 21:42.218
[LAUGHS]

21:42.218 --> 21:43.510
What's the count?

21:43.510 --> 21:45.138
Including the ones
that you brought,

21:45.138 --> 21:47.681
we have a dozen that are ready,
and that leaves 28 to go.

21:47.681 --> 21:49.767
We still need to do
finishing touches on the tree

21:49.767 --> 21:51.102
and the backdrop
for the play.

21:51.102 --> 21:52.645
And it's
getting late.

21:52.645 --> 21:54.730
Do you think they work
this hard in the North Pole?

21:54.730 --> 21:56.107
The next time
I see Santa,

21:56.107 --> 21:57.399
I'm gonna ask him.

21:57.399 --> 21:59.986
[CHUCKLES]
Abigail...

22:01.570 --> 22:04.157
[♪♪♪]

22:20.881 --> 22:22.925
[BANGS DOOR SHUT]

22:23.968 --> 22:25.261
Abigail...

22:25.261 --> 22:27.596
What time is it?
It's nearly 3:00.

22:27.596 --> 22:28.806
Where's Clara?

22:28.806 --> 22:30.891
I sent her upstairs
to take a break.

22:30.891 --> 22:32.434
How're things going
at the saloon?

22:32.434 --> 22:34.145
Well, people
are fading fast.

22:34.145 --> 22:36.689
We're gonna have to do something
if we want to finish on time.

22:36.689 --> 22:38.356
Yeah.

22:38.356 --> 22:40.776
I guess it's time
for my secret weapon.

22:42.111 --> 22:43.696
You have a secret weapon?

22:43.696 --> 22:45.781
Special blend of coffee
from south of the border.

22:45.781 --> 22:47.491
I used it when I tracked
"Billy the Kid"

22:47.491 --> 22:48.826
to the coast of Mexico.

22:48.826 --> 22:50.744
Stayed awake
for three straight days.

22:50.744 --> 22:53.789
Oh. Well, let's not make it
that strong.

22:53.789 --> 22:56.167
I'll boil the water.

22:56.959 --> 23:00.129
[♪♪♪]

23:01.047 --> 23:02.506
[♪♪♪]

23:23.319 --> 23:26.030
[♪♪♪]

23:40.794 --> 23:43.672
[♪♪♪]

23:59.813 --> 24:03.692
[♪♪♪]

24:25.047 --> 24:28.259
[EXHALES]

24:28.259 --> 24:29.635
Good morning.

24:29.635 --> 24:31.929
Oh, good morning.

24:31.929 --> 24:35.266
I'm so tired I can barely move,
but we got it all done.

24:35.266 --> 24:36.809
Good.

24:36.809 --> 24:39.103
And we finished the place
for the Lawson family.

24:39.103 --> 24:41.230
And the stove?

24:41.230 --> 24:43.232
Well, George Edwards
fixed it,

24:43.232 --> 24:44.608
so I'm gonna
take it over there

24:44.608 --> 24:46.444
as soon as I can find
a volunteer with a wagon.

24:46.444 --> 24:49.155
It just so happens
I have one of those!

24:49.155 --> 24:50.572
You're on, Sam.

24:52.741 --> 24:54.743
[CHUCKLES]

24:56.120 --> 24:57.746
This is gonna
sound crazy,

24:57.746 --> 24:58.998
but I'm kind of glad

24:58.998 --> 25:01.499
the freight train
didn't come through.

25:01.499 --> 25:03.210
You're right.

25:03.210 --> 25:05.838
That does sound crazy.

25:05.838 --> 25:07.589
I always knew
the people of Hope Valley

25:07.589 --> 25:09.342
really cared about each other,

25:09.342 --> 25:11.093
but I never realized
how much.

25:11.093 --> 25:12.552
Well, I guess
good things

25:12.552 --> 25:14.013
really do happen
when plans change.

25:14.013 --> 25:16.223
Truer words
were never spoken.

25:16.223 --> 25:18.809
I'll hitch up the horse
and we can go get that stove.

25:18.809 --> 25:20.811
Sounds good.

25:23.147 --> 25:25.149
Good work.

25:25.149 --> 25:26.775
You too.

25:28.444 --> 25:30.863
[FIRE CRACKLING]

25:30.863 --> 25:32.281
[HOOVES CLOPPING]

25:32.281 --> 25:33.782
Pastor!

25:33.782 --> 25:35.575
You wouldn't by chance
have a cup of coffee

25:35.575 --> 25:37.495
for a weary traveler,
would ya?

25:37.495 --> 25:39.038
Of course.

25:39.038 --> 25:41.999
What are you doing
way out here?

25:41.999 --> 25:44.293
I was worried about
you and your mom.

25:44.293 --> 25:46.170
NANCY:
You don't
have to worry about us.

25:46.170 --> 25:48.339
We'll be fine.

25:51.967 --> 25:53.719
So where
are you headed?

25:53.719 --> 25:55.637
Someplace new.

25:58.140 --> 26:00.393
There are too many memories
in Hope Valley.

26:00.393 --> 26:01.685
They're not all bad.

26:01.685 --> 26:04.230
It's where your father
died, Harper.

26:04.230 --> 26:05.981
It's where he taught me
how to fish.

26:05.981 --> 26:07.274
And where I made friends.

26:07.274 --> 26:08.484
Harper.

26:08.484 --> 26:09.902
You still have
friends there,

26:09.902 --> 26:11.862
and they'd like
you to come back.

26:11.862 --> 26:14.990
And I'd like you to finish up
your coffee and leave.

26:14.990 --> 26:17.743
I already said I don't want
anything from you.

26:17.743 --> 26:20.162
Yeah, you did.

26:20.162 --> 26:24.291
Then I remembered a prayer
I learned a long time ago...

26:24.291 --> 26:26.544
Lord, let me be
an instrument of Thy peace.

26:26.544 --> 26:28.462
Where there is hatred,
let me sow love,

26:28.462 --> 26:30.506
where there is doubt, faith...

26:30.506 --> 26:32.007
...Where
there is despair,

26:32.007 --> 26:33.300
hope,

26:33.300 --> 26:34.676
where there is darkness,

26:34.676 --> 26:36.303
light,
and where there is sadness--

26:36.303 --> 26:38.305
[TOGETHER]
...Joy.

26:39.639 --> 26:41.350
Saint Francis' prayer.

26:41.350 --> 26:43.018
My dad taught it to me.

26:43.018 --> 26:44.770
It was his favorite.

26:44.770 --> 26:47.106
I didn't know.

26:47.106 --> 26:48.524
I think your husband

26:48.524 --> 26:51.026
would like you
to come back, Nancy.

26:51.026 --> 26:54.154
Dad was the one who brought us
to Hope Valley, Mama.

26:54.154 --> 26:57.199
You used to say that
he always knew what was best.

26:58.325 --> 27:00.160
FRANK:
I think he still does.

27:01.828 --> 27:04.957
[♪♪♪]

27:08.794 --> 27:10.879
Whoa!

27:10.879 --> 27:12.339
Thanks, Sam.

27:12.339 --> 27:13.673
My pleasure.

27:14.674 --> 27:15.968
Good boy.

27:22.682 --> 27:24.143
Hey, Jack!
You got a minute?

27:24.143 --> 27:25.852
Yeah, Lee.

27:25.852 --> 27:29.231
Hey. I just took the stove
to the Lawsons' place.

27:29.231 --> 27:31.275
Uh, some of the ladies
are cleaning it up now.

27:31.275 --> 27:33.110
Oh, great. Well, then
I have more good news.

27:33.110 --> 27:36.029
Remember the gift that I bought
for Rosemary that went missing?

27:36.029 --> 27:38.031
The pin?
The pin. Yes. Well...

27:38.031 --> 27:39.699
turns out that
it was at the bottom

27:39.699 --> 27:41.452
of the trunk after all.

27:41.452 --> 27:43.996
It slipped behind the lining.
I don't know what happened.

27:43.996 --> 27:45.998
Anyway, I'm really sorry
if I caused any trouble.

27:45.998 --> 27:47.916
No trouble at all.
I'm just glad you found it.

27:47.916 --> 27:50.127
Me too, and I can't wait to see
Rosemary's face

27:50.127 --> 27:51.711
when she opens that box.

27:51.711 --> 27:54.089
I bet she's going to be
surprised and delighted.

27:54.089 --> 27:56.216
I hope so. Anyway,
I'll see you tonight, okay?

27:58.927 --> 28:00.846
I think if we put the buffet
against the wall

28:00.846 --> 28:02.264
and move the tables out,

28:02.264 --> 28:04.350
there'll be enough
standing room for everyone.

28:04.350 --> 28:06.143
Christmas is officially
back on track!

28:06.143 --> 28:07.520
Oh, except
that you and Jack

28:07.520 --> 28:09.062
didn't get to go
to the Mountie Ball.

28:09.062 --> 28:10.606
It was the right
decision to stay.

28:10.606 --> 28:11.898
[FOOTSTEPS]

28:11.898 --> 28:13.192
Can I go play with Robert?

28:13.192 --> 28:15.068
Yes, if you are back
in time to get ready

28:15.068 --> 28:16.320
for the pageant.

28:16.320 --> 28:17.613
Okay.

28:17.613 --> 28:19.781
ELIZABETH:
Cody, where's your baseball?

28:19.781 --> 28:23.035
I...traded it.

28:23.035 --> 28:26.788
Traded it? With who?

28:31.835 --> 28:33.170
Mrs. Stanton!

28:33.170 --> 28:34.672
I don't think

28:34.672 --> 28:36.840
we've had the pleasure
of a formal introduction.

28:36.840 --> 28:38.300
No, but I've heard
all about you,

28:38.300 --> 28:40.219
and I know you've
met my little boy.

28:40.219 --> 28:41.595
Cody.
Yeah, I saw him earlier.

28:41.595 --> 28:42.888
Oh, I'm not looking for him.

28:42.888 --> 28:44.473
I came to talk to you.

28:44.473 --> 28:45.765
About the baseball.

28:45.765 --> 28:47.434
It was a fair trade.

28:47.434 --> 28:49.269
May I ask
what he got in exchange?

28:49.269 --> 28:50.979
Humanity. Kindness.

28:50.979 --> 28:52.898
Everything Christmas
is all about.

28:52.898 --> 28:55.526
I don't think
you answered my question.

28:55.526 --> 28:57.570
Cody traded that ball

28:57.570 --> 28:59.530
for something
one of his friends wanted.

28:59.530 --> 29:00.989
He said she'd
be heartbroken

29:00.989 --> 29:02.616
if she didn't
get it for Christmas.

29:02.616 --> 29:04.076
A "Biddy Betsy" doll?

29:04.076 --> 29:05.494
One and the same!

29:05.494 --> 29:06.912
And you had one?

29:06.912 --> 29:09.039
Yes, indeed! It's funny
how those kind of things

29:09.039 --> 29:10.708
just work out sometimes.

29:10.708 --> 29:12.834
He really loved that baseball.

29:12.834 --> 29:15.379
I can't believe
he did that for Maggie.

29:15.379 --> 29:17.214
He's a pretty special
young man.

29:17.214 --> 29:18.716
Yes, he is.

29:19.883 --> 29:22.302
We're serving
Christmas Eve dinner tonight

29:22.302 --> 29:23.596
for everyone in town.

29:23.596 --> 29:25.723
I-- Well, I hope
you'll join us.

29:25.723 --> 29:27.474
Well, that's a fine invitation,

29:27.474 --> 29:29.476
but I think
I'm heading out soon.

29:29.476 --> 29:31.770
Don't want
to wear out my welcome.

29:31.770 --> 29:34.481
Well, if you change your mind,
we'd love to have you.

29:34.481 --> 29:35.982
How about you,
Mrs. Stanton?

29:35.982 --> 29:38.068
Any last-minute shopping to do?

29:38.068 --> 29:40.028
Oh, I think I've got
Christmas taken care of.

29:40.028 --> 29:41.988
You sure you haven't
forgotten anyone?

29:41.988 --> 29:44.408
I'm sure.

29:44.408 --> 29:46.201
Well...

29:46.201 --> 29:47.869
there is Henry Gowen.

29:47.869 --> 29:50.789
But he doesn't want anything
from me, or anyone else.

29:50.789 --> 29:52.040
Yeah, I saw him out for a walk.

29:52.040 --> 29:53.875
He looked like
a real sourpuss to me.

29:53.875 --> 29:55.085
That's him, all right.

29:55.085 --> 29:56.336
So...

29:56.336 --> 29:58.171
why are you worried
about him at all?

29:59.798 --> 30:01.800
I don't know.

30:01.800 --> 30:03.969
Maybe because
he's one of us,

30:03.969 --> 30:05.887
for better or worse.

30:05.887 --> 30:07.847
Have you told him that?

30:07.847 --> 30:09.516
Well, he didn't
give me a chance.

30:09.516 --> 30:12.603
He said I was pretending to care
to keep up appearances.

30:12.603 --> 30:14.354
Oh, that
can't be true.

30:14.354 --> 30:16.940
It's not.

30:16.940 --> 30:18.858
Well... Ah.

30:18.858 --> 30:20.402
Guess I'm right out of luck.

30:20.402 --> 30:21.903
Well, how's that?

30:21.903 --> 30:24.698
Because the best gift
you can give Old Sourpuss

30:24.698 --> 30:26.199
for Christmas

30:26.199 --> 30:27.743
is the truth.

30:27.743 --> 30:29.911
Even though I'd rather
sell you a necktie.

30:29.911 --> 30:31.371
[LAUGHS]

30:31.371 --> 30:33.081
I think I will
pass on that.

30:33.081 --> 30:34.833
[CHUCKLING]

30:36.042 --> 30:38.796
Thank you for everything,
Mr. Bailey.

30:38.796 --> 30:40.589
You've been a real angel.

30:40.589 --> 30:43.300
Oh, I have been called worse.

30:43.300 --> 30:45.969
[CHUCKLES]

30:58.524 --> 31:00.693
[KNOCKING]

31:04.237 --> 31:06.281
Meant to lock that door.

31:10.202 --> 31:12.037
I thought we were done here.

31:12.037 --> 31:13.455
We were.

31:13.455 --> 31:16.709
And then someone
started me thinking...

31:18.168 --> 31:20.253
And I realized something...

31:21.463 --> 31:24.257
There's a reason
you're here, Henry.

31:24.257 --> 31:27.927
There's a reason
you came back.

31:27.927 --> 31:29.763
I don't need
to listen to this right now.

31:29.763 --> 31:31.515
Yes, you do.

31:31.515 --> 31:35.018
And you're gonna hear me out,
whether you like it or not.

31:35.018 --> 31:38.271
You came back to Hope Valley
because this is your home,

31:38.271 --> 31:40.691
and the people here
are your family.

31:41.734 --> 31:44.027
You need us, Henry.

31:45.278 --> 31:47.197
And the truth is,

31:47.197 --> 31:49.783
I need you.

31:49.783 --> 31:52.536
So you were right after all.

31:53.620 --> 31:56.874
I am here for me.

31:56.874 --> 31:58.876
I'm here because
I have a town to run,

31:58.876 --> 32:01.127
and I need your help to do it.

32:01.127 --> 32:03.463
And I won't let you
push me away.

32:03.463 --> 32:05.340
I'll be back tomorrow,

32:05.340 --> 32:08.552
and the day after that
and the day after that.

32:08.552 --> 32:11.764
Because I'm giving you
a second chance for Christmas.

32:12.806 --> 32:15.559
A chance to work together.

32:15.559 --> 32:18.103
And a chance to start over.

32:19.688 --> 32:21.815
Merry Christmas, Henry.

32:21.815 --> 32:24.526
And welcome home.

32:25.778 --> 32:28.572
[♪♪♪]

32:35.788 --> 32:37.414
ELIZABETH:
And the glory of the Lord

32:37.414 --> 32:40.667
shone round about them,
and they were sore afraid.

32:40.667 --> 32:42.836
But the angel said unto them...

32:42.836 --> 32:44.254
Fear not,

32:44.254 --> 32:45.714
for behold,

32:45.714 --> 32:47.299
I bring you good
tidings of great joy,

32:47.299 --> 32:48.842
which shall be
to all people.

32:48.842 --> 32:51.136
For, unto you
is born this day,

32:51.136 --> 32:52.387
in the city of David

32:52.387 --> 32:54.556
a Savior
which is Christ the Lord.

32:54.556 --> 32:56.099
And this shall be
a sign unto you--

32:56.099 --> 32:57.601
you shall find the babe

32:57.601 --> 33:01.647
wrapped in swaddling clothes
and lying in the manger.

33:12.157 --> 33:13.492
[♪♪♪]

33:13.492 --> 33:17.203
♪ Away in the manger ♪

33:17.203 --> 33:20.332
♪ No crib for his bed ♪

33:20.332 --> 33:23.042
♪ The little Lord Jesus ♪

33:23.042 --> 33:26.755
♪ Lay down his sweet head ♪

33:26.755 --> 33:30.300
♪ The stars
In the night sky ♪

33:30.300 --> 33:33.595
♪ Looked down where he lay ♪

33:33.595 --> 33:36.890
♪ The little Lord Jesus ♪

33:36.890 --> 33:39.434
♪ Asleep on the hay ♪

33:39.434 --> 33:42.061
[ALL APPLAUDING]

33:45.482 --> 33:46.859
You mind if I say
a few words?

33:46.859 --> 33:48.861
Oh, of course!

33:51.780 --> 33:53.740
I don't have a sermon
prepared for you tonight.

33:53.740 --> 33:55.909
It's hard to follow
the greatest story ever told,

33:55.909 --> 33:57.494
so I won't even try.

33:57.494 --> 33:59.746
But I do want to remind everyone

33:59.746 --> 34:01.748
that the greatest gift
we receive

34:01.748 --> 34:03.834
is God's love.

34:03.834 --> 34:05.878
The greatest gift
that we give

34:05.878 --> 34:08.463
is the love we have
for one other.

34:09.506 --> 34:11.466
Merry Christmas, everyone.

34:11.466 --> 34:12.926
[OVERLAPPING]
Merry Christmas!

34:12.926 --> 34:14.761
[TOGETHER]
Merry Christmas.

34:14.761 --> 34:16.513
Merry Christmas.

34:16.513 --> 34:20.141
All right, everyone, well,
I believe our program is over,

34:20.141 --> 34:23.729
unless, of course,
I'm forgetting something.

34:25.981 --> 34:27.524
CHILDREN:
Santa!

34:27.524 --> 34:30.903
Oh, no!
How could I forget Santa?

34:30.903 --> 34:33.112
Ho, ho, ho, ho!

34:33.112 --> 34:38.368
Merry Christmas, boys and girls!
Merry Christmas!

34:38.368 --> 34:40.620
Now, that is a sight
I never thought I'd live to see.

34:40.620 --> 34:42.664
Well, my money's
on you for next year.

34:42.664 --> 34:44.958
You can't keep winning
at darts forever, my friend.

34:44.958 --> 34:46.877
"SANTA" BILL:
Merry Christmas, everyone!

34:46.877 --> 34:48.879
Well...

34:48.879 --> 34:51.590
I believe this one is...

34:51.590 --> 34:53.466
for Timmy.

34:53.466 --> 34:55.594
That's me!

34:58.013 --> 34:59.514
Merry Christmas, young man.

34:59.514 --> 35:01.140
Thank you.

35:02.935 --> 35:04.853
Who's Ruby?

35:04.853 --> 35:08.147
That's me!

35:08.147 --> 35:10.316
Is this really for me?

35:10.316 --> 35:12.318
Yes, it is.
Merry Christmas.

35:14.529 --> 35:18.116
Is there someone here
named Maggie?

35:18.116 --> 35:20.577
Biddy Betsy!

35:20.577 --> 35:22.662
Merry Christmas!

35:24.163 --> 35:27.125
[♪♪♪]

35:28.627 --> 35:31.046
[QUIETLY]
I know what you did for Maggie,

35:31.046 --> 35:33.172
and I'm very proud
of you.

35:33.172 --> 35:35.759
[DOOR OPENS AND SHUTS]

35:36.551 --> 35:39.054
[♪♪♪]

35:46.227 --> 35:48.354
"SANTA" BILL:
This says it's for Harper!

35:48.354 --> 35:50.231
That's me.

35:50.231 --> 35:52.525
Merry Christmas, son.

35:52.525 --> 35:55.570
Merry Christmas,
children. Come!

35:55.570 --> 35:57.447
Merry Christmas!

35:57.447 --> 35:59.574
[♪♪♪]

36:02.368 --> 36:05.080
[LIGHT LAUGHTER
AND QUIET CONVERSATIONS]

36:06.123 --> 36:08.416
I have to lock up
the jail.

36:08.416 --> 36:09.960
Save me a seat
if you can?

36:09.960 --> 36:12.295
Oh, I'm pretty sure
we'll be standing.

36:14.255 --> 36:15.507
All we need now
is some snow

36:15.507 --> 36:17.383
for a perfect
Christmas Eve.

36:17.383 --> 36:18.802
Well, I don't know.

36:18.802 --> 36:20.637
It's pretty clear
for that.

36:20.637 --> 36:22.848
Maybe I'm asking
too much.

36:24.474 --> 36:27.019
Looks like everyone
enjoyed themselves.

36:27.978 --> 36:29.771
I believe they did.

36:29.771 --> 36:31.606
I'm surprised to see
you're still here.

36:31.606 --> 36:34.192
Isn't there somewhere else
you're supposed to be tonight?

36:34.192 --> 36:36.361
Not that I know of.

36:36.361 --> 36:38.613
Think again.

36:50.042 --> 36:51.501
How much?

36:51.501 --> 36:53.294
No charge.

36:56.214 --> 36:57.924
Jesse!

36:57.924 --> 36:59.592
I need your help
with something.

36:59.592 --> 37:01.302
Of course.

37:01.302 --> 37:02.637
What can I do for you?

37:04.181 --> 37:06.307
Mr. Bailey!

37:06.307 --> 37:09.186
Are you sure you don't want
to join us for supper?

37:09.186 --> 37:13.065
Well, that's very kind of you,
but it's time for me to leave.

37:13.065 --> 37:15.108
I hope you'll come back
and visit us.

37:15.108 --> 37:16.526
I will.

37:16.526 --> 37:19.278
But, in the meantime,
I have a favor to ask.

37:19.278 --> 37:21.614
I have a long trip ahead of me,
and...

37:21.614 --> 37:24.201
Dasher here,
he never signed up for that.

37:24.201 --> 37:26.203
He needs a real home.

37:26.203 --> 37:29.831
Do you know anyone in town
I could trust to look after him?

37:29.831 --> 37:31.833
Someone...kind?

37:31.833 --> 37:33.752
With a good heart?

37:34.961 --> 37:37.714
I know
the perfect person.

37:37.714 --> 37:39.007
You really mean it?

37:39.007 --> 37:40.967
If you promise to take
care of each other.

37:40.967 --> 37:43.428
I promise!
I promise! I promise!

37:43.428 --> 37:44.804
[BARKS]

37:46.973 --> 37:49.851
[♪♪♪]

37:49.851 --> 37:52.270
Come on, Dasher!

37:53.980 --> 37:56.482
[♪♪♪]

37:57.400 --> 37:58.985
ELIZABETH:
And so...

37:58.985 --> 38:01.320
with a little help
from a simple peddler

38:01.320 --> 38:03.990
who knew exactly
what everyone needed,

38:03.990 --> 38:05.784
what looked
like disappointment

38:05.784 --> 38:07.493
turned into
a Christmas miracle.

38:08.828 --> 38:10.496
The new families
from the settlement

38:10.496 --> 38:11.998
were able to move

38:11.998 --> 38:14.667
out of the tents
and into real homes.

38:14.667 --> 38:19.005
Rosemary was surprised
and delighted

38:19.005 --> 38:21.340
with Lee's unique gift.

38:22.884 --> 38:24.803
And the warmth
of the Christmas spirit

38:24.803 --> 38:28.181
was rediscovered and reborn.

38:38.024 --> 38:39.776
By the time I got home,

38:39.776 --> 38:42.237
I didn't think there could be
a more perfect Christmas,

38:42.237 --> 38:45.364
but it turned out...

38:45.364 --> 38:47.450
I was wrong.

38:47.450 --> 38:50.162
[♪♪♪]

38:56.417 --> 38:59.378
"The pleasure of your company
is requested at the saloon.

38:59.378 --> 39:01.631
Formal attire."

39:06.469 --> 39:08.721
[DOORS CREAKING]

39:10.765 --> 39:13.268
[♪♪♪]

39:24.445 --> 39:26.239
[MUSIC BOX BEGINS TO PLAY]

39:26.239 --> 39:28.783
[♪♪♪]

39:38.543 --> 39:41.046
May I have this dance,
Miss Thatcher?

39:44.924 --> 39:47.719
I would be delighted,
Constable Thornton.

39:50.680 --> 39:53.350
[♪♪♪]

40:27.133 --> 40:30.303
[♪♪♪]

40:40.521 --> 40:42.065
Giddyap!

40:42.065 --> 40:44.901
[♪♪♪]

40:57.205 --> 40:58.664
[♪♪♪]
